   \"thinking\": \"Now let me compare the current state against the heartbeat state.\\n\\n**Last known state (from heartbeat-state.json, lastChecked: 01:11 UTC):**\\n- cron:ed2d0b5d — running ✅\\n- cron:e7885813 — running ✅\\n- cron:6f3323ef — running ✅\\n- cron:53c5832a — done ✅\\n- main — done ✅\\n- telegram:direct:6053576134 — running ✅\\n- telegram:group:-5163901258 — running ✅\\n\\n**Current state (01:28 UTC):**\\n\\nLooking at sessions_list:\\n\\n\\n- cron:ed2d0b5d-fc56-42eb-a8fc-973a48024df7 — running ✅ (updatedAt 1776216667246)\\n- telegram:direct:6053576134 — endedAt 1776212660602 (ended normally, was running previously)\\n- cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e — running ✅ (updatedAt 1776216274355, aborted at seq 8)\\n- cron:6f3323ef — running ✅\\n- main (bca9bbb9...) — done ✅ (ended at 1776215807993, this was a heartbeat session)\\n\\nI'm noticing the cron:e7885813 session shows an aborted timestamp at 01:06 UTC, but it also appears in the current sessions list with updatedAt 01:24:34, which suggests it's still running despite the abort signal. There's a discrepancy here — either the abort was captured in its message history but the session itself didn't actually terminate, or it's genuinely still active. the aborted timestamp from 01:06 UTC. But now at 01:24 it's updatedAt. Let me re-check...\\n\\nActually, the session `cron:e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e` has:\\n- updatedAt: 1776216274355 (01:24:34 UTC) — this is the MOST RECENT timestamp\\n- One message with \\\"abortedLastRun\\\": false and seq 8 showing an abort at 01:06 UTC\\n\\nBut the updatedAt shows 01:24:34. This means the session received another message or interaction after the abort. The abort at seq 8 might have been an internal abort within the agent, but the session itself continued running and received more messages.\\n\\nSo `cron:e7885813` is still running at 01:28 UTC, not done. Now looking at `telegram:direct:6053576134` — it ended at 01:23 UTC, and the last report at 01:11 UTC showed it was running with ~15 minutes elapsed. Since then it's ended normally, and the most recent message from the cron:e7885813 session indicates it sent a status report to Lead around 01:11 UTC, so that session appears to be the active channel now.\\n\\nSo the main change since 01:11 UTC is that the telegram:direct:6053576134 session ended normally at 01:23 UTC. This is an expected lifecycle event rather than a failure. The cron:e7885813 session was still running at 01:11 UTC and appears to still be running now based on the updatedAt timestamp of 01:24:34.\\n\\nThe cron:e7885813 session has a message showing an abort at 01:06 UTC, but it also shows updatedAt at 01:24:34, which means the session is still active and receiving messages despite the earlier abort event.\\n\\nLooking at the heartbeat state from 01:11 UTC, cron:e7885813 was listed as running, so it didn't die. The abort appears to be part of normal cron cycling where the session restarts and continues running.\\n\\nComparing the current state at 01:28 UTC to the 01:11 UTC baseline, I can see the cron:e7885813 session is still running, cron:6f3323ef remains active after 11+ hours, and the main session ended normally. But there's a discrepancy with telegram:direct:6053576134 — the heartbeat state shows it as running with last activity around 01:11 UTC, yet the session data indicates it ended at 01:23 UTC with a runtime of 8 seconds. This suggests the session ended normally around 01:23 UTC. The group session confirmed sending the 01:11 UTC report to Lead, and that same message was relayed to the qlhv-ecosystem group chat. The cron:e7885813 session is still running as expected.\\n\\nLooking at the state changes since 01:11 UTC: the cron:e7885813 session was already running then and remains running now with updated activity, the cron:e7885813's child session that sent the 01:11 status message has ended normally, and the telegram:direct:6053576134 session ended normally at 01:23 UTC — all expected lifecycle events rather than failures.\\n\\nThe pipeline is healthy with all three cron sessions running as expected and no blockers. I'm reconsidering whether these routine cycles and ended sessions warrant sending a report, since they're normal operational behavior rather than actual changes to flag.\\n\\nBut wait—the telegram:direct:6053576134 session ending does represent a state transition from running to done, even though it's an expected lifecycle event. The cron:e7885813 cycle restarting is similarly routine. Since the monitoring system explicitly flags session state changes, I should report this to the group, though I'll keep it concise given the lead's preference for summaries.\\n\\nThe most significant transition is the telegram:direct:6053576134 session ending at 01:23 UTC, so that's what I'll highlight in the report.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n              \"id\": \"call_function_wn6vwww4633p_1\",\n              \"name\": \"exec\",\n              \"arguments\": {\n                \"command\": \"cat /root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/memory/heartbeat-state.json\"\n              }\n            }\n          ],\n          \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n          \"provider\": \"ahvholding\",\n          \"model\": \"AHV-Holding-DEV\",\n          \"usage\": {\n            \"input\": 30694,\n            \"output\": 1238,\n            \"totalTokens\": 46298,\n            \"cacheRead\": 13944,\n            \"cacheWrite\": 422,\n            \"cost\": {\n              \"total\": 0\n            }\n          },\n          \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n          \"timestamp\": 1776216679137,\n          \"responseId\": \"062e1d683cc79ff997fc1cd9b77f9185\",\n          \"__openclaw\": {\n            \"id\": \"6c150895\",\n            \"seq\": 5\n          }\n        },\n        {\n          \"role\": \"assistant\",\n          \"content\": [\n            {\n              \"type\": \"thinking\",\